name: jiraprinter
description:
This is a very simple app that queries JIRA to list all of the stories in the team's current sprint, and provide an HTML page with print-optimized CSS rules.

Each story is printed out as a half-page (US Letter) card, with the Story number, the summary, and the priority. As a bonus, a QR code is provided which will take you directly to the story from your smartphone.

name: CoreFramework
description:
PHP framework based on plugin system.

The CoreFramework is built around a 300 lines single file that architect all other components as independent plugins. They are loaded in a list and can surcharge anything declared by their predecessors. Each plugin can register an autoloader, command-line functions or declare variables to load as JavaScript or CSS resource.

name: fusiondirectory

FusionDirectory provides a solution to daily management of data stored in an LDAP directory.

Becoming the cornerstone of the information system, the corporate directory becomes more complex offering more and more data and manage more and more infrastructure services.

repo_public_justification: https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=summary

repo_distributed_justification: The project uses GIT https://libvirt.org/downloads.html
version_unique_justification: Release number policy is documented https://libvirt.org/downloads.html
version_semver_justification: Semantic versioning is designed to allow apps to use major version digit to indicate ABI incompatible changes. The libvirt project promises to never make ABI incompatible changes, so semvar is not a necessary format. The release numbering format is strictly time based and documented  https://libvirt.org/downloads.html
version_tags_justification: All releases have corresponding tags in GIT https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=summary
release_notes_justification: Each major release has a NEWS file update summarizing changes https://libvirt.org/news.html
release_notes_vulns_justification: The security notice archive provides formal machine readable data on all security vulnerabilities and which historical releases are affected and/or fixed https://security.libvirt.org/
report_process_justification: None security bugs are accepted via bugzilla, while security bugs are submitted to the security response team directly https://libvirt.org/bugs.html
report_responses_justification: The project monitors its upstream bugzilla service, and user reports on the mailing lists and/or stack overflow
enhancement_responses_justification: The project monitors its upstream bugzilla service, and user reports on the mailing lists and/or stack overflow
report_archive_justification: The bugzilla service is searchable https://libvirt.org/bugs.html
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Private security bugs are to be reported directly to the security response team via a private mailing address https://libvirt.org/securityprocess.html
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Private security bugs are to be reported directly to the security response team via a private mailing address https://libvirt.org/securityprocess.html
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: Bugs reported to the security response team mailing list get an initial response within days, and aim to keep any embargo period to less than 2 weeks.  https://libvirt.org/securityprocess.html
build_common_tools_justification: It is built using GNU autotools https://libvirt.org/compiling.html
build_floss_tools_justification: It is built using GNU autotools and all libraries it depends on are required to be GPLv2.1/LGPLv2.1+ compatible https://libvirt.org/compiling.html
test_justification: There are three automated test suites https://libvirt.org/testsuites.html
test_invocation_justification: The unit tests are invokable using 'make check' https://libvirt.org/testsuites.html
test_most_justification: Code coverage level is not tracked
test_policy_justification: There are multiple tests suites for the code which are contributed to https://libvirt.org/testsuites.html
tests_are_added_justification: There are multiple tests suites for the code which are contributed to https://libvirt.org/testsuites.html
warnings_justification: All possible GCC compile warnings are enabled except for those which cause false positives https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=blob;f=m4/virt-compile-warnings.m4;hb=HEAD
warnings_fixed_justification: The code is required to be 100% warning free at all times, as it builds with -Werror https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=blob;f=m4/virt-compile-warnings.m4;hb=HEAD
warnings_strict_justification: The code is required to be 100% warning free at all times, as it builds with -Werror https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=blob;f=m4/virt-compile-warnings.m4;hb=HEAD
know_secure_design_justification: Understanding security best practices is a core competency of the development team leaders
know_common_errors_justification: Internal APIs have been designed to eliminate entire classes of common security bugs, with a focus around command execution and memory allocation, as well as regularly running automated tests such as coverity https://libvirt.org/internals/command.html https://libvirt.org/hacking.html
crypto_published_justification: The library uses strong crypto from common libraries (GNUTLS, nettle, libgcrypt)
crypto_call_justification: The library uses crypto from common libraries (GNUTLS, nettle, libgcrypt)
crypto_floss_justification: The library uses crypto from common libraries (GNUTLS, nettle, libgcrypt)
crypto_keylength_justification: The project relies on GNUTLS default priorities which are typically configured by the OS vendor to be able to meet such requirements. THere is the ability to override the defaults to enable stronger policies both at build time and runtime.
crypto_working_justification: The default network facing protocols all work with strong cryptographic algorithms by default. Some optional features may still make use of MD5 in non-network scenarios due to need for interoperability with 3rd party software, but this is not required by default.
crypto_pfs_justification: The TLS based network protocol is able to be configured with PFS by default
crypto_password_storage_justification: Password authentication is delegated to the SASL / Kerberos libraries which provide strong storage of credentials.
crypto_random_justification: The project uses GNUTLS for crytographic key generation
delivery_mitm_justification: The RPC protocol can use with TLS or SASL with Kerberos
delivery_unsigned_justification: The project has no need to retrieve checksums
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: The security process aims to fix all vulnerabilities within 2 weeks https://libvirt.org/securityprocess.html
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: The security process aims to fix all vulnerabilities within 2 weeks https://libvirt.org/securityprocess.html
static_analysis_justification: The GNULIB syntax-check facility is used to analyse all commits for common style problems and/or usage of forbidden functions. The coverity tool is also run against the codebase nightly
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: The coverity tool is also run against the codebase nightly
static_analysis_fixed_justification: The project aims to fix security bugs within 2 weeks https://libvirt.org/securityprocess.html
static_analysis_often_justification: The GNULIB syntax-check facility is used to analyse all commits for common style problems and/or usage of forbidden functions. The coverity tool is also run against the codebase nightly
dynamic_analysis_justification: The project does not yet use fuzzing tools
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The project makes use of valgrind to analyse code, and enables make compiler protections during build including _FORTIFY_SOURCE which does runtime bounds checks in key syscalls.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: The projects coding policy is to report errors back up the call stack, rather than immediately aborting/asserting. So there are no asserts for the tools to check unless they analyse the error reporting logic
crypto_weaknesses_justification: The default network facing protocols all work with strong cryptographic algorithms by default. Some optional features may still make use of MD5 in non-network scenarios due to need for interoperability with 3rd party software, but this is not required by default.
discussion_justification: https://libvirt.org/contact.html
no_leaked_credentials_justification: No credentials are stored in public repositories
hardening_justification: The project builds with compiler & linker hardening flags enabled by default
crypto_used_network_justification: The network protocol is configured to require TLS by default, requiring explicit admin action to disable it
crypto_tls12_justification: The project relies on GNUTLS which enables TLS 1.2 by default
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: The project always performs TLS x509 certification verification unless explicitly instructed not to
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: The TLS handshake and verification must be completed before any protocol level traffic is sent
hardened_site_justification: X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: The project is built & installed with GNU autotools, and available for all major Linux distros in their native packaging format, and for Windows using an MSI installer
bus_factor_justification: The project has a broad core team with rights to approve & commit code https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=blob_plain;f=AUTHORS.in;hb=HEAD
documentation_roadmap_justification: The development of project features are a response to requirements of individual contributors working on the project. The project thus has no need to provide a formal roadmap for the project as a whole
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: The project is a program library, so user interface interaction is the concern of applications above.
internationalization_justification: Translations are maintained across many languages https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=tree;f=po;hb=HEAD
sites_password_security_justification: The primary dev host uses /etc/shadow standard hashing scheme.  The wiki based on mediawiki has salted md5 hashes only.
maintenance_or_update_justification: Every release is required to be a drop-in upgrade from the previous version. The library promises API & ABI compatibility.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: All security vulnerabilities are recorded in machine readable XML format with full history of the flaw http://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt-security-notice.git;a=tree
coding_standards_justification: Coding guidelines are primarily documented in the website https://libvirt.org/hacking.html   but also replicated in the source reop
coding_standards_enforced_justification: The project uses the GNULIB 'syntax-check' facility for validating coding styles where practical, along with custom written tools for more complex scenarios
build_standard_variables_justification: The configure script & makefile will honour flags set by the user. This is used during RPM builds
build_preserve_debug_justification: Debugging symbols are enabled by default in all builds
installation_standard_variables_justific: The build system honours DESTDIR and this is validated by RPM builds
installation_development_quick_justifica: The project uses standard GNU autotools framework that allows easy install & test. It can also correctly operate if run from the build directory without install
interfaces_current_justification: The project aims to avoid using dangerous libc APIs where practical (ie all non-reentrant APIs are forbidden).  Other dangerous/easily misused APIs (malloc/free) are wrapped in higher level safe constructs to provide compile time guarantees of correct usage.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: The CI system runs across all commits in git master branches https://ci.centos.org/view/libvirt/
implement_secure_design_justification: Access to the APIs requires authentication by default when accessing any privileged resources. The network listener service requires TLS by default. Internal APIs are designed to be robust against incorrect usage in key areas.
input_validation_justification: The API and RPC layers both do validation of user input to reject incorrect/unsafe defaults.
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: The use of GNUTLS is controlled by system crypto configuration policies which can be changed by the local admin whenever required.
crypto_credential_agility_justification:
API authentication is delegated to external libraries (SASL, Kerberos, etc).

Storage of passwords for VMs is handled out of band from the main VM configuration to avoid  credential compromise in logs
contributors_unassociated_justification: There are contributors with commit access from multiple organizations https://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=blob_plain;f=AUTHORS.in;hb=HEAD  and historical contributions for many organizations
copyright_per_file_justification: Contributors include copyright statements in all new non-trivial source files
license_per_file_justification: All source files have a copyright header present
two_person_review_justification: All changes have mandatory review by someone other than the author unless falling under limited exceptions (trivial fix, critical build breaker fix)
